Window Functions
👉 Window Functions = used in analytics, reports, dashboards, interviews
🧠 What are Window Functions?
👉 Window functions perform calculations across a set of rows
👉 BUT they do NOT group rows (unlike GROUP BY)

💡 Key Idea
GROUP BY → reduces rows
Window Function → keeps all rows + adds extra column

📘 Example Table: employees
name	dept	salary
Rahul	IT	50000
Amit	IT	60000
Neha	HR	40000
Ravi	HR	45000

🔑 Basic Syntax
FUNCTION() OVER (
  PARTITION BY column
  ORDER BY column
)

🧩 1. ROW_NUMBER() (Ranking)
👉 Gives unique rank (no duplicates)
SELECT name, salary,
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank
FROM employees;

🧠 Output
name	salary	         rank
Amit	60000 	1
Rahul	50000	            2
Ravi	45000	            3
Neha	40000	4

🧩 2. RANK()
👉 Same rank for same values (skips numbers)
SELECT name, salary,
RANK() OVER (ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank
FROM employees;

🧩 3. DENSE_RANK()
👉 Same rank but no skipping

🧠 Difference
Function	       Duplicate Rank	   Skip
ROW_NUMBER	❌ No	             ❌ No
RANK	                         ✅ Yes	✅ Yes
DENSE_RANK	             ✅ Yes	❌ No

🧩 4. PARTITION BY (Group without grouping 🔥)
👉 Like GROUP BY but keeps rows
SELECT name, dept, salary,
ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY dept ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rank
FROM employees;

🧠 Output
name	dept	salary	       rank
Amit	IT	60000 	1
Rahul	IT	50000	            2
Ravi	HR	45000	            1
Neha	HR	40000	2

👉 Ranking inside each department

🧩 5. SUM() OVER (Running Total)
SELECT name, salary,
SUM(salary) OVER (ORDER BY salary) AS running_total
FROM employees;

🧩 6. AVG() OVER
SELECT name, salary,
AVG(salary) OVER () AS avg_salary
FROM employees;
👉 Shows average on every row

🧩 7. LAG() and LEAD() (Very Important 🔥)
🔹 LAG (previous row)
SELECT name, salary,
LAG(salary) OVER (ORDER BY salary) AS prev_salary
FROM employees;

🔹 LEAD (next row)
SELECT name, salary,
LEAD(salary) OVER (ORDER BY salary) AS next_salary
FROM employees;
---
🧠 Real-Life Use Cases
Top N employees per department
Running totals (sales)
Compare current vs previous data
Leaderboards
Salary analysis
---
🔥 Interview Question Example
👉 Top 2 salaries per department:
SELECT *
FROM (
  SELECT name, dept, salary,
  ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY dept ORDER BY salary DESC) AS rn
  FROM employees
) t
WHERE rn <= 2;
